Description: Methyltransferase enzyme first described in Streptoalloteichus tenebrarius. Confers resistance to aminoglycosides (esp. apramycin) through methylation of the 16S rRNA at A1408, thereby modifying the target.
NpmA is a plasmid-mediated aminoglycoside-resistance 16S rRNA methyltransferase by interfering w/ aminoglycoside binding w/ the A site of 16S rRNA through N-1 methylation at position A1408.

ArmA is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase that targets mature or nearly mature 30S subunits. It transfers a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to N7-G1405 of the 16S rRNA, an aminoglycoside binding site.
RmtA is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase found in P. aeruginosa which methylates G1405 of the 16S rRNA. It confers high level resistance to many aminoglycosides.

RmtB is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase that targets mature or nearly mature 30S subunits. It transfers a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to N7-G1405 of the 16S rRNA, an aminoglycoside binding site.

RmtC is a rRNA methyltransferase found in Proteus mirabilis w/ high level resistance to similar to aminoglycosides, w/ the exception of non-4,6-disubstituted deoxystreptamines (streptomycin and neomycin). It has also been isolated in Salmonella enterica ser. Virchow. It is hypothesized to methylate G1405, like related methyltransferases RmtA, RmtB, and ArmA.
RmtD is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase found in P. aeruginosa which methylates G1405 of the 16S rRNA. It confers high level resistance to many aminoglycosides.
The first allele of a 16S rRNA methyltransferase gene, rmtD2, confers a high resistance to all clinically available aminoglycosides

ribD is a M.tuberculosis riboflavin biosynthesis enzyme. Point mutations in ribD cause enzyme overexpression, which allows the C-terminal reductase domain to act as an alternative dihydrofolate reductase. Thus, mutations in ribD confer resistance to DHFR inhibitors such as para-aminosalicylic acid.

MprF is a integral membrane protein that modifies the negatively-charged phosphatidylglycerol on the membrane surface. amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Heterologous expression of Burkholderia pseudomallei Omp38 (BpsOmp38) in Omp-deficient E. coli host cells lowers their permeability and in consequence, their antimicrobial susceptibility to penicillin G, cefoxitin, ceftazidime and imipenam.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: The E.coli ompF (oprF) is a nonspecific porin channel involved in the membrane translocation of small hydrophilic molecules, including and especially beta-lactams. Mutations in ompF can decrease diffusion ofs across the cellular membrane, thereby decreasing overall susceptibility through absence of porin function.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Mutant forms of the porin Omp36 result in reduced permeability tos.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Klebsiella pneumoniae outer membrane porin protein. In beta-lactam-resistant Klebsiella, this porin is often deleted, limiting diffusion of the into the cell. Klebsiella strains expressing OmpK35 are often beta-lactam sensitive even in the presence of beta-lactamases because of an inefficient mechanism.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Klebsiella pneumoniae outer membrane porin protein. In beta-lactam-resistant Klebsiella, this porin is often deleted, limiting diffusion of the into the cell. Klebsiella strains expressing OmpK36 are often beta-lactam sensitive even in the presence of beta-lactamases because of an inefficient mechanism.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Klebsiella pneumoniae outer membrane porin protein. Is preferentially detected in porin-deficient strains. Functional characterization of this new porin revealed a narrower pore than those of porins OmpK35 and OmpK36, which did not allow penetration by certain beta-lactams. Also, when a resistant strain expresses porin OmpK37 is less susceptible to cefotaxime and cefoxitin than when it is expressing either OmpK36 or OmpK35.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: The outer membrane protein M35 of Moraxella catarrhalis is an antigenically conserved porin. Down-regulation of M35 significantly increases the MICs of aminopenicillins, specifically amoxicillin.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Mutant forms of the porin Por result in reduced permeability tos, particularly tetracyclines and beta-lactams.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: In the presence of stress, there is a coupled down-regulation of the porin OmpC w/ the OmpF.  Mutants both lacking both OmpC and OmpF proteins are resistant to cephaloridine and cefazolin. Analyses of genes involved in the increased resistance to tetracycline suggest that the up-regulation of efflux pump genes is accompanied by a decrease of OmpF and OmpC synthesis. Homologs of OmpC have been identified in E.coli, Salmonella enterica, Klebsiella aerogenes and Serratia marcescens.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to beta-lactams
Description: Omp1 is an outer membrane porin that confers resistance by absence in S. marcescens.  Knockout, deletion or other inhibition of the omp1 gene confers resistance to certain beta-lactamases - including Cefoxitin, Ceftriaxone, Cefotaxime, and Moxalactam - as well as Ciprofloxacin, Tetracycline, and Chloramphenicol, by preventing passage of the into the cell.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to peptides
Description: A ToxR negatively regulated outer membrane porin. In Vibrio cholerae, ToxR controls resistance to P2 (a BPI-derived antimicrobial peptide) by regulating the production of OmpT, especially in the absence of OmpU.

amr_gene_family: General Bacterial Porin w/ reduced permeability to peptides
Description: A ToxR-Regulated outer membrane porin. In Vibrio cholerae, ToxR controls resistance to P2 (a BPI-derived antimicrobial peptide) by regulating the production of OmpU. OmpU also confers resistance to polymyxin B sulfate.

The mphA gene encodes for resistance enzyme MPH(2')-I which preferentially inactivate 14-membered macrolides (e.g.erythromycin, telithromycin, roxithromycin) over 16-membered macrolides (e.g.tylosin, spiramycin). It phosphorylates macrolides at 2'-OH hydroxyl of desosamine sugar of macrolides in a GTP-dependent manner.

The mphB gene encodes for MPH(2')-II. This enzymes phosphorylates 14-membered and 16-membered macrolides.  It phosphorylates macrolides in GTP- dependent manner at 2'-OH hydroxyl of desosamine sugar of macrolides.
The mphC gene was identified from S.aureus.  This gene shows similarity to mphB gene from Escherchia coli.
mphE is a macrolide phosphotransferase and resistance gene identified on a plasmid, pRSB105
mphF is a macrolide phosphotransferase and resistance gene identified on the IncP plasmid pRSB111
The mphG gene encodes a macrolide 2'-phosphotransferase found in Photobacterium damselae sharing sequence similarity to mphA in E. coli.
A chromosomal macrolide 2'-phosphotransferase and resistance gene identified from a Brachybacterium faecium cave isolate

mphI is a macrolide phosphotransferase protein found in Paenibacillus sp. LC231, a strain of Paenibacillus isolated from Lechuguilla Cave, NM, USA. Confers resistance to macrolides. Described by Pawlowski et al. 2016.
A chromosomal macrolide phosphotransferase identified in Brevibacillus brevis VM4.
A chromosomal macrolide phosphotransferase identified from Bacillus subtilis
mphL is a chromosomally-encoded macrolide phosphotransferases that inactivate 14- and 15-membered macrolides such as erythromycin, clarithromycin, azithromycin.
mphM is a chromosomally-encoded macrolide phosphotransferases that inactivate 14-, 15- and 16-membered macrolides.
A macrolide phosphotransferase identified on a plasmid in Exiguobacterium
A chromosomal macrolide phosphostransferase identified in Brachybacterium paraconglomeratum
Expression of abaF in E. coli resulted in increased resistance to fosfomycin.
AbaQ is an MFS transporter mainly involved in the extrusion of quinolone-type drugs in A. baumannii

AmvA has 14 alpha-helical transmembrane segments, qualifying it as a member of the DHA2 transporter family of the major facilitator superfamily (MFS). When AmvA was expressed in E. coli,  the cells had at least four-fold decreased susceptibility to erythromycin, acridine orange, acriflavine, deoxycholate and methyl viologen. AmvA from the AC0037 strain of A. baumannii was tested.
ArlR is a response regulator that binds to the norA promoter to activate expression. ArlR must first be phosphorylated by ArlS.
ArlS is a protein histidine kinase that phosphorylates ArlR, a promoter for norA expression.

Transmembrane protein which expels bicyclomycin from the cell, leading to bicyclomycin resistance. Identified in P. aeruginosa strains responsible for outbreaks in Brazil, often appearing w/ blaSPM-1, another bicyclomycin resistance gene
blt is an MFS efflux pump that confers resistance to multiple drugs such as rhodamine and acridine dyes, and fluoroquinolones
bmr is an MFS efflux pump that confers resistance to multiple drugs including acridine dyes, fluoroquinolones, chloramphenicol, and puromycin
cmlA1 is a plasmid or transposon-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in P. aeruginosa and Klebsiella pneumoniae
cmlA4 is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Klebsiella pneumoniae
cmlA5 is a plasmid or transposon-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in E.coli
cmlA6 is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in P. aeruginosa
cmlA8 is a plasmid that confers resistance to chloramphenicol.
cmlB is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Klebsiella aerogenes
cmlB1 is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Bordetella bronchiseptica
cmrA is a transposon-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Rhodococcus rhodochrous
cmx is a plasmid or transposon-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Corynebacterium striatum and P. aeruginosa.
tetAB genes of the Corynebacterium striatum R-plasmid which encode an ABC transporter and confer tetracycline, oxytetracycline, and oxalic resistance
Multidrug efflux pump in E. coli. This multidrug efflux system was originally identified as the Cmr/CmlA chloramphenicol exporter.
efmA is an MFS transporter permease in  E. faecium.
efpA is an MFS transporter found in M.tuberculosis.
EmrA is a membrane fusion protein, providing an efflux pathway w/ EmrB and TolC between the inner and outer membranes of E. coli, a Gram-negative bacterium.
emrB is a translocase in the emrB -TolC efflux protein in E. coli. It recognizes substrates including carbonyl cyanide m-chlorophenylhydrazone (CCCP), nalidixic acid, and thioloactomycin.
EmrD is a multidrug transporter from the Major Facilitator Superfamily (MFS) primarily found in E.coli. EmrD couples efflux of amphipathic compounds w/ proton import across the plasma membrane.
emrK is a membrane fusion protein that is a homolog of EmrA. Together w/ the inner membrane transporter EmrY and the outer membrane channel TolC, it mediates multidrug efflux.
EmrR is a negative regulator for the EmrAB-TolC multidrug efflux pump in E. coli. Mutations lead to EmrAB-TolC overexpression.
emrY is a multidrug transport that moves substrates across the inner membrane of the Gram-negative E. coli. It is a homolog of emrB.

Efflux protein facT confers resistance to factumycin. The gene has been heterologously expressed in S. coelicolor and its function was confirmed (Thaker et al. Med. Chem. Commun. 2012, 3: 1020). It is possible that this gene can efflux other kirromycin-like elfamycins, but this has not been tested.
farA is the membrane fusion protein that is part of the farAB efflux pump.
farB is the cytoplasmic transporter protein that is part of the farAB efflux pump. farB corresponds to 3 loci in P. aeruginosa PAO1 and 3 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58.
fexA is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Staphylococcus lentus
floR is a plasmid or chromosome-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Bordetella bronchiseptica, E.coli, Klebsiella pneumoniae,
hp1181 is a translocase that is part of the MFS efflux pump family. It is found in H. pylori and has role in the active efflux ofs.

KpnE subunit of KpnEF resembles EbrAB from E. coli. Mutation in KpnEF resulted in increased susceptibility to cefepime, ceftriaxon, colistin, erythromycin, rifampin, tetracycline, and streptomycin as well as enhanced sensitivity toward sodium dodecyl sulfate, deoxycholate, dyes, benzalkonium chloride, chlorhexidine, and triclosan

KpnF subunit of KpnEF resembles EbrAB from E. coli. Mutation in KpnEF resulted in increased susceptibility to cefepime, ceftriaxon, colistin, erythromycin, rifampin, tetracycline, and streptomycin as well as enhanced sensitivity toward sodium dodecyl sulfate, deoxycholate, dyes, benzalkonium chloride, chlorhexidine, and triclosan.

KpnG consists of ~390 residues and resembles EmrA of E. coli. Disruption of the pump components KpnG-KpnH signficantly decrease resistance to azithromycin, ceftazidime, ciprofloxacin, ertapenam, erythromycin, gentamicin, imipenam, ticarcillin, norfloxacin, polymyxin-B, piperacillin, spectinomycin, tobramycin, and streptomycin

KpnH consists of ~511 residues, resembles EmrB of E. coli, and is probably a translocase in the KpnGH-TolC efflux protein in K. pneumoniae. Disruption of the pump components KpnG-KpnH signficantly decrease resistance to azithromycin, ceftazidime, ciprofloxacin, ertapenam, erythromycin, gentamicin, imipenam, ticarcillin, norfloxacin, polymyxin-B, piperacillin, spectinomycin, tobramycin, and streptomycin.
lfrA is involved in the active efflux of quinolones and is found in Mycobacteroides abscessus.
lmrP is a proton motive force-dependent drug transporter that is part of the MFS efflux pump family.

The MdtG protein, also named YceE, appears to be a member of the major facilitator superfamily of transporters, and it has been reported, when overexpressed, to increase fosfomycin and deoxycholate resistances. mdtG is a member of the marA-soxS-rob regulon.
Multidrug resistance protein MdtH
Multidrug resistance protein MdtM
Multidrug resistance efflux pump. Could be involved in resistance to puromycin, acriflavine and tetraphenylarsonium chloride.
Multidrug resistance efflux pump. Could be involved in resistance to puromycin, acriflavine and tetraphenylarsonium chloride
Multidrug resistance efflux pump. Could be involved in resistance to puromycin, acriflavine and tetraphenylarsonium chloride
mef(B) is a macrolide efflux gene located in the vicinity of sul3 in E.coli. There is also a mefB found in Streptococcus agalactiae that confers resistance to macrolides.
NBU2-encoded resistance gene. An MefE homolog in Bacteroides species. Macrolide efflux MFS transporter
mefC is a macrolide efflux gene isolated from a plasmid in Photobacterium damselae.
mefE is a proton motive efflux pump in Streptococcus pneumoniae that confers resistance to macrolides. It is found on the same operon as mefA and the ABC-efflux pump mel.

NorA is a multidrug efflux pump in S.aureus that confers resistance to fluoroquinolones and other structurally unrelateds like acriflavine. It shares 30% similarity w/ NorA, and is a structural homolog of Bmr of Bacillus subtilis. It is regulated by arlRS and mgrA, the latter also known as NorR.

NorB is a multidrug efflux pump in S.aureus that confers resistance to fluoroquinolones and other structurally unrelateds like tetracycline. It shares 30% similarity w/ NorB, and is a structural homolog of Blt of Bacillus subtilis. It is regulated by mgrA, also known as NorR.
otr(B) is a tetracycline resistance efflux pump found in Streptomyces rimosus
pexA is a florfenicol and chloramphenicol resistance gene discovered in Alaskan soil.
PmrA is a MFS-type efflux pump expressed in Streptococcus pneumoniae that confers low-level resistance to norfloxacin, ciprofloxacin, and acriflavine.
pp-flo is a plasmid chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Photobacterium damselae subsp. piscicida
qacA is a subunit of the qac multidrug efflux pump
qacB is a subunit of the qac multidrug efflux pump
QepA1 is a plasmid-mediated efflux pump in E. coli, shown to contribute to fluoroquinolone resistance. It is regulated by sox genes, also known as global stress regulators.
QepA2 is a plasmid-mediated quinolone resistance pump found in an E.coli isolate from France

A plasmid-mediate quinolone efflux pump described in Klebsiella aerogenes and E.coli. QepA3 confers resistance to fluoroquinolones by expelling the molecules from the cell. This is distinct from the usual chromosomal mutation mechanism of quinolone resistance. Described by Wang et al. 2017.
A plasmid-mediated quinolone efflux pump variant described in E.coli. QepA4 confers resistance to quinolone and fluoroquinolones by expulsion from the cell. Described by Manageiro et al. 2017.
cmr is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Rhodococcus fascians and Corynebacterium glutamicum
rosA is part of an efflux pump/potassium antiporter system (RosAB) in Yersinia that confers resistance to cationic antimicrobial peptides such as polymyxin B.
rosB is part of an efflux pump/potassium antiporter system (RosAB) in Yersinia that confers resistance to cationic antimicrobial peptides such as polymyxin B.

NorA gene cloned from S.aureus conferred relatively high resistance to hydrophilic quinolones such as norfloxacin, enoxacin, ofloxacin, and ciprofloxacin in S. aureus and E.coli. Had low or no resistance at all to hydrophobic ones such as nalidixic acid, oxolinic acid, and sparfloxacin in S. aureus and E.coli.
cmlA is a plasmid-encoded chloramphenicol exporter that is found in Salmonella typhimurium

MFS transporters are secondary active transporters w/ single-polypeptide chains containing 400-600 amino acids that transport small solutes across the membrane by using electrochemical gradients. LmrS has 14 transmembrane helices and, when expressed in E. coli, is capable of extruding a variety ofs inclinding linezolid, trimethoprim, florfenicol, chlorampheniocol, erythromycin, streptomycin, kanamycin, and fusidic acid
cmlR is a plasmid or chromosome-encoded chloramphenicol resistance determinant (putative transmembrane protein) that is found in E.coli and Streptomyces lividans
Efflux pump proteins contained w/in Mycobacterial genomes which confer resistance to a number of differents including aminoglycosides, and tetracyclines.
Major facilitator superfamily transporter. Resistance to tetracenomycin C by an active tetracenomycin C efflux system which is probably energized by transmembrane electrochemical gradients.
tcr3 is a tetracycline efflux pump that confers self-resistance to Kitasatospora aureofaciens
Tet30 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in agrobacterium, a Gram-negative bacterium.
Tet31 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Aeromonas salmonicida, a Gram-negative bacteria. It has also been shown to be expressed in Gallibacterium anatis.
Tet33 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-positive bacteria, including Arthrobacter and Corynebacterium.
Tet38 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-positive S.aureus. It is regulated by mgrA, which also regulates NorB.
Tet39 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-negative bacteria, including Brevundimonas, Stenotrophomonas, Enterobacter, Alcaligenes, A., and Providencia.
Tet40 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in the Gram-positive Clostridium. It is similar to tetA(P).
Tet41 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Serratia, a Gram-negative bacterium.  It is related to A. Tet(39).
Tet42 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in both Gram-negative (P.) and Gram-positive (Microbacterium, Bacillus, Staphylococcus, Paenibacillus) bacteria.
Tet(43) is a tetracycline resistance gene w/ unknown origins, isolated from metagenomic DNA.
tet45 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Bhargavaea cecembensis strain previously isolated from a poultry-litter-impacted soil.
Tet(59) is a chromosome-encoded tetracycline efflux pump described from a Chinese pig manure sample.
TetA is a tetracycline efflux pump found in many species of Gram-negative bacteria.
Tet(B) is a tetracycline efflux protein expressed in many Gram-negative bacteria. It confers resistance to tetracycline, doxycycline, and minocycline, but not tigecycline.
Tet(C) is a tetracycline efflux pump found in many species of Gram-negative bacteria. It is typically found in plasmid DNA.
TetD is a tetracycline efflux pump found exclusively in Gram-negative bacteria.
TetE is a tetracycline efflux pump found in many Gram-negative bacteria, especially those in water environments. The gene is found on large plasmids.

TetG is a tetracycline efflux protein found in Gram-negative bacteria. The encoding gene is found in both chromosomal and plasmid DNA where it is frequently linked to the floR, sul1, and cmlA9 genes which encode proteins that can confer florfenicol/chloramphenicol, sulfamethoxazole, and chloramphenicol resistance, respectively.

TetH is a tetracycline efflux protein expressed in Gram-negative bacteria (Actinobacillus, A., Gallibacterium, Histophilus, Mannheimia, Moraxella, Pasteurella, and Psychrobacter). Its gene is linked to the resistance genes sul2, and strAB, which confer resistance to sulfamethoxazole and streptomycin, respectively.
TetJ is a tetracycline efflux protein expressed in Gram-negative bacteria (Escherichia, Morganella, and Proteus).
TetK is a tetracycline efflux protein found in both Gram-negative (Haemophilus and Gallibacterium) and Gram-positive (many species, including mycobacteria) bacteria.
TetL is a tetracycline efflux protein found in many species of Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria.
TetV is a tetracycline efflux protein that has been found in Mycolicibacterium smegmatis and Mycolicibacterium fortuitum.
TetY is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Gram-negative bacteria (Aeromonas and Escherichia). It is associated w/ plasmid DNA.
TetZ is a tetracycline efflux protein found in Gram-positive bacteria (Corynebacterium and Lactobacillus). It is associated w/ plasmid DNA.
TetA(58) is a Tetracycline efflux pump described in Paenibacillus sp. LC231, a strain of Paenibacillus isolated from Lechuguilla Cave, NM, USA. Described by Pawlowski et al. 2016.
TetA(P) is a inner membrane tetracycline efflux protein found on the same operon as the ribosomal protection protein TetB(P). It is found in Clostridium, a Gram-positive bacterium.
Tetracycline resistant TetB(58) efflux pump found in Paenibacillus sp. LC231, a strain of Paenibacillus isolated from Lechuguilla Cave, NM, USA. Described by Pawlowski et al. 2016.

TetR is the repressor of the tetracycline resistance element; its N-terminal region forms a helix-turn-helix structure and binds DNA. Binding of tetracycline to TetR reduces the repressor affinity for the tetracycline resistance gene (tetA) promoter operator sites. Mutations arise w/in tetR results in lower affinity for tetracyclin
Class G tetracycline resistance determinant from Vibrio anguillarum
Tetracycline-resistant determinant encoded on the plasmid pKQ10 in

amr_gene_family: major facilitator superfamily (MFS) efflux pump;resistance-nodulation-cell division (RND) efflux pump
Description: EvgA, when phosphorylated, is a positive regulator for efflux protein complexes emrKY and mdtEF. While usually phosphorylated in a EvgS dependent manner, it can be phosphorylated in the absence of EvgS when overexpressed.

amr_gene_family: major facilitator superfamily (MFS) efflux pump;resistance-nodulation-cell division (RND) efflux pump
Description: EvgS is a sensor protein that phosphorylates the regulatory protein EvgA. evgS corresponds to 1 locus in P. aeruginosa PAO1 and 1 locus in P. aeruginosa LESB58.

Description: MtrR is a repressor of mtrCDE expression. Mutations in mtrR increase multidrug resistance.

MCR-5 is a transposon-associated phosphoethanolamine transferase gene, identified in Salmonella Paratyphi B dTa+ (d-tartrate fermenting Salmonella enterica subsp. enterica serovar Paratyphi B) isolates from food-producing animals. The isolates were collected between 2011 and 2013, and retrieved from the German National Reference Laboratory for Salmonella. MCR-5 confers resistance to collistin through the addition of a phosphoethanolamine group to lipid A, causing a reduction in negative charge of the cell membrane. Described by Borowiak et al, 2017.

mecD is a PBP2a variant identified on a genomic resistance island in Macrococcus caseolyticus. MecD confers resistance to methicillin and other beta-lactams through the production of an alternative low-affinity PBP. mecI acts as a repressor of transcription of the mecA/mecR1/mecI operon.

A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the mgtA gene in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin, calcomycin, rosaramicin, methymycin, and pikromycin, while interactions w/ erythomycin, oldeandomycin, azithromycin, and tylosin were weaker. It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin. Mechanism first described by Cundliffe, 1992.
MltA-interacting protein (mipA), is an resistance-related outer membrane protein. Deletion of mipA increases kanamycin, nalidixic acid and streptomycin resistance.

amr_gene_family: multidrug and toxic compound extrusion (MATE) transporter
Description: MepR is an upstream repressor of MepA in S.aureus. It is part of the mepRAB operon.

amr_gene_family: multidrug and toxic compound extrusion (MATE) transporter
Description: PmpM is a multidrug efflux pump belonging to the MATE family of P. aeruginosa. PmpM is an H+ drug antiporter and is the first reported case of an H+ coupled efflux pump in the MATE family. PmpM confers resistance to fluoroquinolones, fradiomycin, benzalkonium chloride, chlorhexidine gluconate, ethidium bromide, tetraphenylphosphonium chloride (TPPCl), and rhodamine 6G.

murA or UDP-N-acetylglucosamine enolpyruvyl transferase catalyses the initial step in peptidoglycan biosynthesis and is inhibited by fosfomycin. Mutations to the murA enzyme confers resistance to the.

Chlamydia murA confers intrinsic resistance to fosfomycin. The presence of an aspartic acid residue in place of the critical cysteine at position 119 that enables fosfomycin binding is believed to be responsible for this intrinsic resistance.

murA or UDP-N-acetylglucosamine enolpyruvyl transferase catalyses the initial step in peptidoglycan biosynthesis and is inhibited by fosfomycin. Overexpression of murA through mutations such as Asp369Asn and Leu370Ile confers fosfomycin resistance. Extensive evidence has shown the significance of C115 mutations in conferring fosfomycin resistance since this residue represents a primary binding site for the across many species.

ChrB is a methyltransferase found in Streptomyces bikiniensis and confers resistance to chalcomycin, mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering). chrB is found in the chalcomycin biosynthetic cluster and is responsible for self-resistance in S. bikiniensis.
A rRNA methyltransferase conferring high-level evernimicin resistance

myrA is a methyltransferase found in Micromonospora griseorubida and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering) of 23S ribosomal RNA. MyrA is found in the mycinamicin biosynthetic cluster and is one mechanism by which M. griseorubida protects itself from self-destruction when producing this macrolide.

RlmA(II) is a methyltransferase found in Streptococcus pneumoniae and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering) of 23S ribosomal RNA.

TlrB is a methyltransferase found in Streptomyces fradiae and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering). TlrB is found in the tylosin biosynthetic cluster and is one mechanism by which S. fradiae protects itself from self-destruction when producing this macrolide.

PNGM-1 is a subclass B3 metallo-beta-lactamase first identified from a deep-sea sediment meta-genome. PNGM-1 is shown to reduce susceptibility to extended- and broad-spectrum cephalosporins, carbapenams, and penicillins. PNGM-1 is a novel metallo-beta-lactamase which predates the current era.

PtsI (phosphoenolpyruvate-protein phosphotransferase) is involved in cyclic AMP synthesis, which regulates glpT expression. As a result, mutations to ptsI confer resistance to fosfomycin by affecting the regulation of fosfomycin import.
pncA is a pyrazinamidase/nicotinamidase. It catalyzes the activation of pyrazinamide. Some mutation w/in pncA are associated w/ loss of enzyme activity, resulting in pyrazinamide resistance.

RpsA, the 30S ribosomal protein S1 of M.tuberculosis, is involved in trans-translation and is targeted by pyrazinonic acid, the active form of the pyrazinamide, which disrupts the initiation of mRNA translation. Mutations in the amino acid sequence of rpsA can confer resistance to pyrazinamide maintaining rpsA function.

mfd dissociates transcription elongation complexes blocked at nonpairing lesions and mediates recruitment of DNA repair proteins. The Mfd (mutation frequency decline) protein, also known as transcription-repair coupling factor, is responsible for ATP-dependent removal of stalled RNA polymerase from DNA lesions by inducing forward movement of the RNA polymerase and subsequent recruitment of nucleotide excision repair machinery to the sites of the lesions.

fabG is a 3-oxoacyl-acyl carrier protein reductase involved in lipid metabolism and fatty acid biosynthesis.The bacterial biocide Triclosan blocks the final reduction step in fatty acid elongation, inhibiting biosynthesis. Point mutations in fabG can confer resistance to Triclosan.

AbuO is akin to the TolC outer membrane efflux protein. Deletion in A. baumannii results in increased susceptibility tos including amikacin, carbenicillin, ceftriaxone, meropenam, streptomycin, and tigecycline as well as disinfectants benzyalkonium chloride and chlorhexidine [PMID25512405].

Protein subunit of AcrA-AcrB-TolC multidrug efflux complex. AcrB functions as a herterotrimer which forms the inner membrane component and is primarily responsible for substrate recognition and energy transduction by acting as a drug/proton antiporter.
AcrD is an aminoglycoside efflux pump expressed in E. coli. Its expression can be induced by indole, and is regulated by baeRS and cpxAR.
AcrE is a membrane fusion protein, similar to AcrA.
AcrF is a inner membrane transporter, similar to AcrB.
AcrS is a repressor of the AcrAB efflux complex and is associated w/ the expression of AcrEF. AcrS is believed to regulate a switch between AcrAB and AcrEF efflux.
AdeA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex AdeABC.
AdeB is the multidrug transporter of the adeABC efflux system.
AdeC is the outer membrane factor of the AdeABC multidrug efflux complex. It can be replaced by other outer membrane channels, and is not essential for resistance.
AdeF is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex AdeFGH.
AdeG is the inner membrane transporter of the AdeFGH multidrug efflux complex.
AdeH is the outer membrane channel protein of the AdeFGH multidrug efflux complex.
AdeI is the membrane fusion protein of the AdeIJK multidrug efflux complex.
AdeJ is a RND efflux protein that acts as the inner membrane transporter of the AdeIJK efflux complex. It has 57% identity w/ E. coli AcrB.
AdeK is the outer membrane factor protein in the adeIJK multidrug efflux complex.
AdeL is a regulator of AdeFGH in A. baumannii. AdeL mutations are associated w/ AdeFGH overexpression and multidrug resistance.
AdeN is a repressor of AdeIJK, a RND-type efflux pump in A. baumannii. Its inactivation increases expression of AdeJ.
AdeR is a positive regulator of AdeABC efflux system. AdeR inactivation leads to susceptibility to aminoglycosides.
AdeS is a sensor kinase in the AdeRS regulatory system of AdeABC. It is essential for AdeABC expression.
amrA is the efflux pump subunit of the AmrAB-OprM multidrug efflux complex. amrA corresponds to 1 locus in P. aeruginosa PAO1 and 1 locus in P. aeruginosa LESB58.
amrB is the membrane fusion protein of the AmrAB-OprM multidrug efflux complex.

ArmR, a 53-amino-acid antirepressor, allosterically inhibits MexR dimer-DNA binding by occupying a hydrophobic binding cavity w/in the center of the MexR dimer. ArmR up-regulation and MexR-ArmR complex formation have previously been shown to upregulate MexAB-OprM.
AxyX is the inner membrane transporter of the AxyXY-OprZ efflux pump system in Achromobacter spp.
AxyY is the periplasmic adaptor protein of the AxyXY-OprZ efflux pump system in Achromobacter spp.
AxyZ is a transcriptional regulator of the AxyXY-OprZ efflux pump system.
BaeR is a response regulator that promotes the expression of MdtABC and AcrD efflux complexes.
BaeS is a sensor kinase in the BaeSR regulatory system. While it phosphorylates BaeR to increase its activity, BaeS is not necessary for overexpressed BaeR to confer resistance.
ceoA is a periplasmic linker subunit of the CeoAB-OpcM efflux pump
ceoB is a cytoplasmic membrane component of the CeoAB-OpcM efflux pump
CmeA is the membrane fusion protein of the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.
CmeB is the inner membrane transporter the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.
CmeC is the outer membrane channel protein of the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.
CmeR is a repressor for the CmeABC multidrug efflux pump, binding to the cmeABC promoter region.
CpxA is a membrane-localized sensor kinase that is activated by envelope stress. It starts a kinase cascade that activates CpxR, which promotes efflux complex expression.
CRP is a global regulator that represses MdtEF multidrug efflux pump expression.
AcrA is a subunit of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux system that in E. coli.
AcrR is a repressor of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux complex. AcrR mutations result in high level resistance. The mutations associated w/ this model are specific to E. coli.

The E.coli CpxR/CpxA system responds to general periplasmic stress and has been used as a model two-component system for transcription regulation in bacteria. CpxR/CpxA system facilitates Salmonella and E. coli resistance to cationic antimicrobial peptides.The CpxR/CpxA system can activate transcription of marRAB operon, thus facilitating multidrug-resistant regulator to enhance expression of TolC-dependent tripartite multidrug transporters.
MarR is a repressor of the mar operon marRAB, thus regulating the expression of marA, the activator of multidrug efflux pump AcrAB.
rob is a positive regulator for the acrAB efflux genes, and is structurally similar to SoxS and MarA.
AcrA is a subunit of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux system that in E. cloacae.
rob is a positive regulator for the acrAB efflux genes, and is structurally similar to SoxS and MarA.

GadW is an AraC-family regulator that promotes mdtEF expression to confer multidrug resistance. GadW inhibits GadX-dependent activation. GadW clearly represses gadX and, in situations where GadX is missing, activates gadA and gadBC.
GadX is an AraC-family regulator that promotes mdtEF expression to confer multidrug resistance.
GolS is a regulator activated by the presence of golD, and promotes the expression of the MdsABC efflux pump.
AcrR is a repressor of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux complex. AcrR mutations result in high level resistance.
AcrA is a subunit of the AcrAB multidrug efflux system that in K. pneumoniae, which is encoded by the acrRAB operon.
AcrR is a repressor of the AcrAB-TolC multidrug efflux complex. AcrR mutations result in high level resistance.
RamR is a repressor that regulates RamA expression. Mutations lead to the upregulation of AcrAB, which is positively regulated by RamA.
LpeA is a subunit of the LpeAB efflux pump in Legionella pneumophila, which is homologous to AcrA in E. coli.
LpeB is a subunit of the LpeAB efflux pump in Legionella pneumophila, which is homologous to AcrB in E. coli.
MdsA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC.
MdsB is the inner membrane transporter of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC. mdsB corresponds to 1 locus in P. aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: mexQ) and 2 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58.
MdsC is the outer membrane channel of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC.
MdtA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex mdtABC.
MdtB is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex w/ MdtC to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex.

MdtC is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex w/ MdtB to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex. In the absence of MdtB, MdtC can form a homomultimer complex that results in a functioning efflux complex w/ a narrower drug specificity. mdtC corresponds to 3 loci in P. aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: muxC/muxB) and 3 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58.
MdtE is the membrane fusion protein of the MdtEF multidrug efflux complex. It shares 70% sequence similarity w/ AcrA.
MdtF is the multidrug inner membrane transporter for the MdtEF-TolC efflux complex.
MexA is the membrane fusion protein of the MexAB-OprM multidrug efflux complex.
MexB is the inner membrane multidrug exporter of the efflux complex MexAB-OprM.
MexC is the membrane fusion protein of the MexCD-OprJ multidrug efflux complex.
MexD is the multidrug inner membrane transporter of the MexCD-OprJ complex.
MexE is the membrane fusion protein of the MexEF-OprN multidrug efflux complex.

MexF is the multidrug inner membrane transporter of the MexEF-OprN complex. mexF corresponds to 2 loci in P. aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: mexF/mexB) and 4 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58 (gene name: mexD/mexB).
MexG is a membrane protein required for MexGHI-OpmD efflux activity.
MexH is the membrane fusion protein of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.
MexI is the inner membrane transporter of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.
mexJ is the membrane fusion protein of the MexJK multidrug efflux protein.
mexK is the inner membrane resistance-nodulation-cell division (RND) transporter in the MexJK multidrug efflux protein.
MexL is a specific repressor of mexJK transcription and autoregulates its own expression.
mexM is the membrane fusion protein of the MexMN-OprM multidrug efflux complex.
MexN is the inner membrane transporter of the MexMN-OprM multidrug efflux complex.
MexP is the membrane fusion protein of the MexPQ-OpmE multidrug efflux complex
MexQ is the inner membrane transporter of the multidrug efflux pump MexPQ-OpmE.
MexR is the repressor of the MexRAB-OprM operon. Mutant forms of mexR result in up-regulation of efflux pump system MexAB-OprM.
MexR is the repressor of the MexRAB-OprM operon. Mutant forms of mexR result in up-regulation of efflux pump system MexAB-OprM.
MexS is a suppressor of MexT, which is an activator of the multidrug pump MexEF-OprN. Mutations in MexS lead to multidrug resistance.
MexT is a LysR-type transcriptional activator that positively regulates the expression of MexEF-OprN, OprD, and MexS.
MexV is the membrane fusion protein of the MexVW-OprM multidrug efflux complex.
MexW is the RND-type membrane protein of the efflux complex MexVW-OprM.
MexX is the membrane fusion protein of the MexXY-OprM multidrug efflux complex.
MexY is the RND-type membrane protein of the efflux complex MexXY-OprM.
MexZ is a transcriptional regulator that downregulates the mexXY multidrug transporter operon, which confers to aminoglycoside resistance on P. aeruginosa.
MtrA is a transcriptional activator of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux pump of Neisseria gonorrhoeae.
MtrC is the membrane fusion protein of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux complex.
MtrD is the inner membrane multidrug transporter of the MtrCDE efflux complex.
MtrE is an outer membrane exporter protein that is part of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux complex.
MuxA is a membrane fusion protein component of the efflux pump system MuxABC-OpmB in P. aeruginosa.
MuxB is one of the two necessary RND components in the P. aeruginosa efflux pump system MuxABC-OpmB.
MuxC is one of the two necessary RND components of the MuxABC-OpmB efflux pumps system in P. aeruginosa.
MvaT, a global regulator of virulence genes in P. aeruginosa, has also shown to be able to repress the expression of the MexEF-OprN pump.
NalC is a repressor of PA3720-PA3719, which are positive regulators of MexAB-OprM. Thus, nalC mutants confer multidrug resistance.
NalD is a repressor of MexAB-OprM. Mutations lead to multidrug resistance and MexAB-OprM overexpression.
OpcM is an outer membrane factor protein found in Burkholderia cepacia. It is part of the CeoAB-OpcM complex.
OpmB is an outer membrane efflux protein in P. aeruginosa that shows functional cooperation w/ MuxABC, to form the efflux pump system MuxABC-OpmB.
OpmD is the outer membrane channel protein of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.
opmE is an outer membrane factor protein that is part of the multidrug efflux pump MexPQ-OpmE.
OpmH is an outer membrane efflux protein required for triclosan-specific efflux pump function.
OprA is an outer membrane factor protein found in P. aeruginosa. It is part of the MexXY-OprA complex.
OprJ is the outer membrane channel component of the MexCD-OprJ multidrug efflux complex.
OprM is an outer membrane factor protein found in P. aeruginosa and Burkholderia vietnamiensis. It is part of the MexAB-OprM, MexVW-OprM, MexXY-OprM and the AmrAB-OprM complex.
OprN is the outer membrane channel component of the MexEF-OprN multidrug efflux complex.
OprZ is the outer membrane component of the AxyXY-OprZ efflux pump system in Achromobacter spp.

Type A NfxB mutants are four to eight times more resistant to ofloxacin, erythromycin, and new zwitterionic cephems, i.e., cefpirome, cefclidin, cefozopran, and cefoselis, than the parent strain, PAO1. nfxB corresponds to 2 loci in P. aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: esrC/nfxB) and 2 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58 (gene name: nfxB).

Type B NfxB mutants are more resistant to tetracycline and chloramphenicol, as well as ofloxacin, erythromycin, and the new zwitterionic cephems, than was PAO1, and they are four to eight times more susceptible to carbenicillin, sulbenicillin, imipenam, panipenam, biapenam, moxalactam, aztreonam, gentamicin, and kanamycin than PAO1. The mutation at the 46th amino acid position is sufficient for overproduction of OprJ and the multidrug resistance. nfxB corresponds to 2 loci in P. aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: esrC/nfxB) and 2 loci in P. aeruginosa LESB58 (gene name: nfxB).

Bifidobacterium are resistant probiotics are prescribed to upkeep the population beneficial bacteria in the gut microbiome. However, horizontal gene transfer among gut microbes could create harmful-resistant pathogenic bacteria, such as M.tuberculosis. Lokesh et al. analyzed Bifidobacterium antitubercular drug resistance and mutations in rpoB. They found that B. animalis, B. longum and B. adolescentis showed considerable resistance to pyrazinamide, isoniazid, and streptomycin, while B. adolescentis had mutations both in the rifampicin (RIF) pocket and in regions outside the pockets, and also showed considerable resistance to RIF.

Non-van ligases that synthesize D-Ala-D-Ala, the default cell wall precursor that makes a cell vulnerable to glycopeptides. Mutations in the ddl gene can cause the production of nonfunctional/inactivated D-Ala-D-Ala ligases, which can render bacteria glycopeptide dependent depending on the presence of vancomycin resistance clusters.

VanA is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that synthesizes D-Ala-D-Lac, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It has been isolated from VREs. It is associated w/ both vancomycin and teicoplanin resistance.

VanB is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog similar to VanA, and can synthesize D-Ala-D-Lac, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It has been isolated from VREs. It is associated w/ vancomycin resistance, but not teicoplanin resistance.

VanC is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that synthesizes D-Ala-D-Ser, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It is specific to Enterococcus gallinarum and E. casseliflavus, providing intrinsic resistance.

VanD is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog similar to VanA, and can synthesize D-Ala-D-Lac, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It is associated w/ both vancomycin and teicoplanin resistance.
VanE is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that can synthesize D-Ala-D-Ser, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity in Enterococcus faecalis

VanG is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that can synthesize D-Ala-D-Ser, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity in Enterococcus faecalis

VanI is a D-Ala-D-Lac ligase that reduces vancomycin binding affinity, helping to confer vancomycin resistance as part of the VanI resistance gene cluster in Desulfitobacterium spp. and Desulfosporosinus spp.
VanL is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that can synthesize D-Ala-D-Ser, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity in Enterococcus faecalis

VanM is a D-Ala-D-Ala ligase homolog that can synthesize D-Ala-D-Lac, an alternative substrate for peptidoglycan synthesis that reduces vancomycin binding affinity. It is associated w/ both vancomycin and teicoplanin resistance.
